import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    zip_counts = data['state'].value_counts()
    zip_counts.plot(kind='bar')
    
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.title("What is the distribution of zip codes across different states?", wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
```

    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
from wordcloud import WordCloud
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    city_names = ' '.join(data['city'].tolist())
    wordcloud = WordCloud(width=480, height=480, margin=0).generate(city_names)
    plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation='bilinear')
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.title("What is the most common city name in the dataset?", wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
```

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    
    # Group by state and county, then count the number of unique counties per state
    county_distribution = data.groupby('state')['county'].nunique()
    
    # Create a stacked bar chart of the number of counties per state
    county_distribution.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True)
    
    # Rotate x-axis labels if necessary
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    
    plt.title("What is the distribution of counties across different states?", wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
```
